{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480413"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:42:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:42:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"48"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:41:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:41:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"48"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"48","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/48"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.8,0.09,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"48"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92403"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"48","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/48"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"48"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75722"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"126"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6038"},{"type":"tags","id":"7231"},{"type":"tags","id":"11093"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92403"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the orthopaedic clinic for follow-up two months after sustaining a left humeral shaft fracture requiring internal fixation. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. While the fracture appears well-healed radiologically, he has difficulty extending his wrist, fingers and thumb. He also reports reduced sensation over the dorsal aspect of his hand. His initial injury X-ray is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely to be injured in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior interosseous nerve","Radial nerve","Median nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Ulnar nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of radial nerve palsy following a humeral shaft fracture. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is particularly vulnerable to injury as it travels in the spiral groove on the posterior aspect of the humerus, where it is tethered to the bone. Injury typically results in weakness of wrist and finger extension (wrist drop) and reduced sensation over the dorsal aspect of the hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior interosseous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is actually a branch of the radial nerve that provides motor function to the extensors of the fingers and thumb. However, as it branches distal to the spiral groove, isolated posterior interosseous nerve injury would not explain the wrist drop or sensory changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects thumb opposition, finger flexion and pronation. It provides sensation to the palmar aspect of the lateral three and a half digits. It is not commonly injured in humeral shaft fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the muscles that flex the elbow (biceps and brachialis) and provides sensation to the lateral forearm. It is not typically affected by humeral shaft fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the intrinsic muscles of the hand and provides sensation to the medial one and a half digits. While it can be injured in distal humeral fractures near the medial epicondyle, it is not typically affected by humeral shaft fractures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The radial nerve is injured in up to 20% of humeral shaft fractures due to its close anatomical relationship with the spiral groove.","Radial nerve injury causes weakness of wrist and finger extension, including thumb extension.","A thorough neurovascular examination is essential in all humeral shaft fractures."],"references":["Bounds EJ, Frane N, Jajou L, et al. Humeral Shaft Fractures. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2023 Dec 13. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448074/","Ricci FP, Barbosa RI, Elui VM, Barbieri CH, Mazzer N, Fonseca Mde C. Radial nerve injury associated with humeral shaft fracture: a retrospective study. Acta Ortop Bras. 2015 Jan-Feb;23(1):19-21. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4544514/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75722"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"48"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17472"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17472"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.